article.description: Katie Smith had 13 points and a career-high 11 rebounds to lead the Detroit Shock to their sixth straight victory, 66-58 over the the Washington Mystics on Saturday night.
article.headline: Ford rests as Shock collect sixth straight victory
article.linkText: Ford sits as Smith leads Shock to sixth straight win
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. -- Already known for her scoring, Katie Smith showed she can rebound, too.

With Cheryl Ford sitting out to rest a sprained right knee, Smith had 13 points and a career-high 11 rebounds to help Detroit beat the Washington Mystics 66-58 Saturday night for the Shock's sixth straight victory.

"Rebounding is an emphasis of ours every game, but we knew we had to step up with Cheryl on the bench," said Smith, who had double-digit rebounds for the second time in her career -- first since getting 10 against Portland in 2001. "I don't get this many very often, though. I'll probably have one in our next game."

Ford, the WNBA's career leader in rebounds per game, rested after playing a combined 77 minutes in games on Wednesday and Friday.

"I'm hoping we can get her back for the next game," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "But we don't know right now -- she's playing heavy minutes and that's when this flares up."

Deanna Nolan and reserves Plenette Pierson and Katie Feenstra added 10 apiece for Detroit (17-5), which took over sole possession of first place in the Eastern Conference -- one game ahead of Indiana.

"We've been wearing our starters out, and we had an emotional win in Indiana last night followed by a five-hour bus ride home," Laimbeer said. "So we built tonight's game plan around the reserves, and they played big."

Alana Beard had 16 points and Nakia Sanford added 11 for the Mystics (9-13), who snapped a four-game winning streak.

With both teams playing for the third time in four days, Detroit held Washington to 13 points in the first half -- the third-lowest total in league history -- on 19 percent shooting.

"They wanted us to shoot from the outside, and we started accepting those shots," Beard said. "We were very passive instead of attacking their zone."

The Mystics didn't help themselves on the boards, either, pulling down only one offensive rebound in the half and four for the game.

"That's great -- that's the reason we won the game," said Smith, third on the WNBA's career scoring list with 4,431 points. "We know Washington gets a lot of second-chance points, and we did a great job of limiting them."

Washington All-Star DeLisha Milton-Jones shot 3-for-15, and Beard was the only Mystics player with more than three field goals.

"Both teams played last night, and we had heavy legs," Washington coach Tree Rollins said. "They went to the zone, and we struggled a way to penetrate the zone."

The Shock blew a 16-point lead in Washington's last visit to The Palace, so they weren't surprised when the Mystics quickly cut the margin to nine.

"We never give up," Rollins said. "That's the thing with my team. We never quit."

Detroit, though, cut off the rally and took a 48-34 advantage into the final period.

"They are always a second-half team, so we knew they would be coming," Smith said. "Luckily, we did enough to hold them off."

The Mystics pulled within 60-52 with 2 minutes to play, but a key offensive rebound by Smith helped Detroit run out the clock.
